[[sn:Tamatsukuri Onsen]] [[en:Tamatsukuri Onsen]]
[[Category:Pages without translation templates]] [[Category:pages with valid en interwikis]] <!--enwiki derived wikidata interwikis--> {{Commons category|Tamatsukuri Onsen}} [[fr:Tamatsukuri onsen]] [[id:Tamatsukuri Onsen]] [[ja:玉造温泉]] [[zh:玉造溫泉]]

{{afc comment|Wikidata entry [[d:Q3514711]] Wikidata name: Tamatsukuri Onsen [[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 09:49, 11 June 2025 (UTC)}} {{short description|Hot spring in Shimane Prefecture, Japan}} [[File:Tamatsukuri onsen01st3200.jpg|300px|thumb|The '''[[Magatama]]''' bridge of Tamatsukuri Onsen]] {{nihongo|'''Tamatsukuri Onsen'''|玉造温泉}} is an [[:en:Onsen|Onsen]] hot spring located in [[:en:Tamayu, Shimane|Tamayu]], [[:en:Shimane Prefecture|Shimane Prefecture]]. The closest large city to the onsen is [[:en:Matsue|Matsue]], which can be accessed by car, bus, or rail. Tamatsukuri is a noted [[:en:sulfate|sulfate]] spring with water temperatures between {{convert|50|-|70|°C|°F}}.<ref name="d">{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Dijitaru Daijisen | title = 玉造温泉 | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-10-23 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Tamatsukuri Onsen | oclc = 56431036 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Encyclopedia of Japan | title = S | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-10-23 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | oclc = 56431036 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Encyclopedia of Japan | title = Tamatsukuri Hot Spring | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-10-23 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | oclc = 56431036 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref>
Tamatsukuri Onsen is an ancient [[:en:Hot spring|Hot spring]], dating back to the 8th century<ref name="jt">{{cite web |title=An ancient hot spring resort by a small river that flows into nearby Lake Shinji |url=https://www.japan.travel/en/spot/931/ |publisher=Japan Travel |access-date=14 May 2021}}</ref> where gods are said to bathe once a year since the creation of Japan according to the myth of [[Izanagi]] and [[:en:Izanami|Izanami]]. The onsen is mentioned as early as 733 in an entry in the Izumo Fudoki, an ancient record of the culture and geography of [[:en:Izumo Province|Izumo Province]].<ref name="d" />
The waters of Tamatsukuri are said to aid in the recovery from several ailments such as rheumatism, skin conditions, etc. The mineral content of the water is said to be beneficial to the skin, and is a popular destination with those interested in the area's ancient history, and its beauty benefits.<ref name="SJ">{{cite web |title=Historical and modern hot spring resort, Tamatsukuri Onsen |date=15 May 2014 |url=https://www.kankou-shimane.com/en/destination/2461 |publisher=Shimane Japan |access-date=14 May 2021}}</ref>
